<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="366" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1255,1894]" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1255,1281]" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Wingspan, 
<quantity box="[405,550,1255,1282]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.875" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.75" pageId="9" pageNumber="366" unit="mm" value="18.75" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="17.5">17.5–20 mm</quantity>
. The species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Park &amp; Karisch" authorityName="Park &amp; Karisch" authorityYear="2022" box="[835,1158,1255,1282]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Thubdora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="366" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ivoryensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[835,976,1256,1281]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">T. ivoryensis</emphasis>
Park &amp; Karisch
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1169,1259,1256,1282]" pageId="9" pageNumber="366" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1169,1253,1256,1282]" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">sp. nov</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
in the forewing pattern, but the forewing has a larger, yellowish-white triangular costal patch, and the female genitalia differ from the latter by the ductus bursae extremely broadened in distal 2/3, with signum absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1255,1894]" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">
<emphasis box="[199,363,1363,1389]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[377,507,1363,1390]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1669,1693]" captionTargetBox="[171,1417,200,1618]" captionTargetId="figure-24@10.[151,1436,181,1645]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Thubdora barbata (Meyrick, 1933): A, Adult; A1, Label; A2, Female; A3, Labial palpus; B1, male genitalia, GU- 3933/Karisch; B, Aedeagus, in SDEI; C, Female genitalia, GU-3897/Karisch, in MNVD." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810522" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810522/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">Figs. 7B, B</figureCitation>
<figureCitation box="[508,519,1364,1390]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1300,1324]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,345,1276]" captionTargetId="figure-101@1.[151,1436,345,1276]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Topographical map of the region Northwest of Man, Black circles = collecting sites; inserted map: Ivory Coast with marked collecting area (arrow) (Openstreetmap, inserted map: Mapsland, CCA 3.0)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810508" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810508/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">1</figureCitation>
): Uncus broadly dilated distally. Valva with elongated, nearly parallel-sided cucullus. Aedeagus narrowed apically; cornuti consisting of series of numerous conical spines. Subgenital segment with a pair of long hair-like pencils
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1255,1894]" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">
<emphasis box="[199,390,1471,1497]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">Female genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[405,495,1471,1498]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1669,1693]" captionTargetBox="[171,1417,200,1618]" captionTargetId="figure-24@10.[151,1436,181,1645]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Thubdora barbata (Meyrick, 1933): A, Adult; A1, Label; A2, Female; A3, Labial palpus; B1, male genitalia, GU- 3933/Karisch; B, Aedeagus, in SDEI; C, Female genitalia, GU-3897/Karisch, in MNVD." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810522" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810522/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="366">Fig. 7C</figureCitation>
): Abdominal sternite VIII narrowed distally, with slight emargination at middle. Ostium bursae convex on caudal margin. Antrum shortened, narrowly broadened, weakly sclerotized, with narrowly extended latero-caudal processes. Ductus bursae extremely broadened in distal half, upper part weakly sclerotized with two long, sclerotized plates and densely wrinkled on lower half, then narrowed, membranous in anterior 1/4. Corpus bursae ovate; signum absent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
